{"data":[{"id":"268nb_v1","type":"preprints","attributes":{"date_created":"2026-06-18T09:40:16.405752","date_modified":"2026-06-26T23:49:50.329777","date_published":"2026-06-26T23:49:50.292134","original_publication_date":null,"custom_publication_citation":null,"doi":null,"title":"Synthesizing Robotics and Cognitive Psychology to Build Tomorrow's Leaders","description":"The global proliferation of young people classified as Not in Education, Employment, or Training (NEET) constitutes one of the most pressing developmental crises of the twenty-first century. Compounding this reality is the rapid acceleration of artificial intelligence (AI) and automation technologies, which are simultaneously displacing established career pathways and generating new demands for interdisciplinary cognitive competence widening existing skill gaps precisely when a generation of learners is most vulnerable. This article proposes a synthesized pedagogical framework that bridges robotics education and cognitive psychology to cultivate well-rounded, future-ready leaders. Drawing on four fundamental domains of knowledge Real (Natural) Sciences, Idea Sciences (Mathematics and Logic), Social Sciences, and the Humanities robot-building is positioned not merely as a technical exercise but as a rich, multidimensional learning environment that mirrors the full complexity of human cognition, collaboration, and meaning-making. The framework accommodates diverse learning styles and argues that intelligent robot construction can serve as a powerful vehicle for holistic development, enhanced social pragmatics, and the formation of adaptive, empathetic leaders equipped to thrive in an AI-accelerated world.","is_published":true,"is_preprint_orphan":false,"license_record":{"copyright_holders":[],"year":null},"tags":["21st Century Skills","AI Literacy","Artificial Intelligence","Career Readiness","Cognitive Psychology","Computational Thinking","Educational Robotics","Educational Technology","Future Skills"